AI Workflow for Developers - Team Project

Overview
This repository contains the shared project for the Emerging Technologies module.
The project demonstrates different AI workflow systems designed by the team members.
Each system uses n8n as an orchestration platform and connects external services such as Azure DevOps, GitHub, GitHub Actions and LLM providers.
This README explains how to start the local n8n environment, import the workflows and execute the different systems.

<br>

Repository Structure
docker-compose.yml
workflows/
n8n_data/
.env
README.md

<br>

Local n8n Self-Hosting Setup
The project uses a self-hosted n8n instance running locally with Docker.
The docker-compose.yml file is already included in the project.
Before starting n8n, the following local resources must be available:
Docker Desktop installed and running
Git installed
The project repository cloned locally
A local .env file if environment variables are required
A local n8n_data directory for persistent n8n data

<br>

Clone the Project Repository
Open a terminal and clone the project repository.
Replace the URL if another remote is used.
git clone [<repository-url>](https://AI-Workflow-Nutrition@dev.azure.com/AI-Workflow-Nutrition/AI-Workflow-Nutrition/_git/AI-Workflow-Nutrition)
cd AI-Workflow-Nutrition

<br>

Prepare Local n8n Data
The n8n_data directory is used to persist the local n8n database and configuration.
If the directory does not exist, create it before starting Docker.
mkdir n8n_data
The .env file can be used for local configuration values if needed.
This file must not be committed.

<br>

Start n8n
From the root of the project, run:
docker compose up -d
n8n is then available at:
http://localhost:5678
At first launch, n8n asks to create a local user account.
This account is only used for the local n8n instance.

<br>

Stop n8n
To stop the local n8n instance:
docker compose down
To restart it later:
docker compose up -d

<br>

Persistent Data
The local n8n data is stored in the n8n_data directory.
This directory is ignored by Git.
The .env file is also ignored by Git because it can contain local configuration values or secrets.
The .gitignore currently contains:
n8n_data
.env

<br>

Import Workflows in n8n
Open n8n at:
http://localhost:5678
Create the local n8n account if it does not already exist.
Open the workflow import menu.
Import the workflow JSON files from the workflows directory.
After import, each workflow can be opened, inspected and executed from the n8n interface.

<br>

Configure Credentials in n8n
The workflows require credentials to connect to external services.
Credentials are not stored in Git.
They must be configured inside the local n8n instance after the workflows are imported.
The main credential types used by the project are:
Azure DevOps Personal Access Token
GitHub Personal Access Token or GitHub Bearer Token
Mistral or OpenAI API Key
Ollama local endpoint, if a local model is used

<br>
## System 1 - Centralized AI Nutrition Workflow

Purpose:
This system demonstrates a centralized AI workflow designed to generate, validate and test a nutrition analysis application.
The workflow uses n8n as the main orchestrator and Ollama as a local LLM runtime.

The goal is to generate an application where a user can enter a meal with foods and quantities.
The application must normalize the input, match foods with the official Swiss food composition database, retrieve real nutritional values through the BLV API and calculate the nutritional totals.

The system focuses on a complete lifecycle:
generation, validation, automatic correction, runtime test and final report.

<br>

Workflows:
The main workflow for System 1 is:

- central-workflow-nutrition

The workflow is organized around the following steps:

1. Design Thinking
Creates the global vision of the project and defines the expected user experience.

2. User Stories and Requirements
Transforms the idea into functional requirements and user stories.

3. App Generation
Generates the application structure, frontend, backend and configuration files.

4. Nutrition Logic
Uses the official BLV API to retrieve real food composition data.
The system must not invent nutritional values.

5. Quality Validation and Correction
Checks the generated application and applies automatic corrections when issues are detected.
The correction loop is limited to avoid infinite executions.

6. Runtime Test and Reporting
Tests the generated application through an HTTP request after it has been started locally.
Generates a final lifecycle report with the execution result, warnings and failures.

<br>

Generated artifacts:
- ready-to-run application zip
- generated source files
- runtime quality test result
- final lifecycle report

<br>

Execution steps:
1. Make sure Ollama is installed, running locally and has the required model.

Commands:
ollama list
ollama pull llama3.2-vision

2. Execute the centralized nutrition workflow manually from n8n.
3. To test the generated application locally, extract the generated zip and start the app.

Commands:
cd app
npm install
npm run dev

4. Once the app is running, execute the runtime HTTP test step in n8n.
5. Review the final lifecycle report generated by the workflow.

<br>

Credentials:
System 1 mainly uses local and public services.

Required configuration:
- Ollama local endpoint
- BLV API endpoint
- Optional Git repository access if generated files are pushed manually

<br>

## Ollama Configuration

Default local endpoint from the host machine:
http://localhost:11434

Default local endpoint from Docker / n8n container:
http://host.docker.internal:11434

Purpose:
Ollama is used to run local LLM calls for generation, correction and reporting.
It reduces cloud API costs and makes repeated local testing easier.

<br>

## BLV API Configuration

Credential type:
No authentication required

Base API:
https://api.webapp.prod.blv.foodcase-services.com/BLV_WebApp_WS/webresources/BLV-api

Purpose:
The BLV API is the official data source for Swiss food composition values.
The application must use real API data and must not generate fake calories, proteins, carbohydrates, fats or micronutrients.

<br>

## Runtime Test

The runtime test checks whether the generated application can be reached through HTTP after being started locally.
If the test fails with ECONNREFUSED, start the app first:

Commands:
cd app
npm install
npm run dev

<br>

## Known Limitations

The generated application may still require manual review.
Some food names can be ambiguous and may need human validation.
The BLV API matching can be improved for spelling mistakes, mixed languages or vague quantities.
The runtime test only works if the generated app is already running locally.

<br>

## Troubleshooting

If Ollama does not respond, check that it is running:

Command:
ollama list

If the app cannot start because the port is already used, stop the existing process or change the application port.
If nutritional values are missing, check the BLV API matching and make sure the application does not use fake fallback values.
