## System 3 - Decentralized AI Software Factory
Purpose:
This system demonstrates a semi-autonomous AI Software Factory based on real User Stories.
It transforms Azure DevOps User Stories into generated code, tests, Git branches, GitHub Actions executions and reporting artifacts.
The workflow chain processes the User Story, generates implementation files, pushes a GitHub branch, triggers CI/CD and stores a final execution report.

<br>

## Azure DevOps Usage
Azure DevOps is used as the backlog and User Story source for this system.
The workflows fetch User Stories from Azure DevOps and update their tags during execution.
The Azure DevOps project must already contain the User Stories to process.
User Stories intended for the decentralized AI workflow must use the expected project tags.
Example tags:
Decentralized
SEQ_001
During execution, the workflow can add tags such as:
AI_PROCESSING
AI_COMPLETED

<br>

## GitHub Usage
GitHub is used as the application repository for this system.
The workflow creates feature branches, writes generated files, commits them and pushes them to GitHub.
GitHub Actions is used to execute the CI pipeline.
Application repository:
https://github.com/ValG-cpu/Nutrition-App

<br>

## Running the System
The execution starts from the master workflow:
WF00 - Master Orchestrator
WF00 fetches the next eligible User Story from Azure DevOps and calls the next workflows in sequence.
The workflow chain processes the User Story, generates implementation files, pushes a GitHub branch, triggers CI/CD and stores a final execution report.

<br>

## Workflow List
Bootstrap - User Story Creation
Creates simple and sequential Azure DevOps User Stories automatically.
Initializes the backlog with small atomic User Stories.
Adds the required project tags such as Decentralized and SEQ_XXX.
This workflow is used before WF00 when the backlog must be prepared automatically.

<br>

WF00 - Master Orchestrator
Coordinates the full execution chain.
Fetches eligible Azure DevOps User Stories.
Initializes the execution payload.
Calls the next workflows.

<br>

WF01 - Requirement Analysis
Analyzes the selected User Story.
Checks clarity, completeness and feasibility.
Produces a requirement analysis artifact.

<br>

WF02 - Technical Design
Produces a technical design from the analyzed User Story.
Defines files, modules, dependencies and implementation constraints.

<br>

WF03 - TDD / Test Design
Generates the test strategy.
Defines expected pytest tests.
Keeps the test scope aligned with the User Story acceptance criteria.

<br>

WF04A - Repository Context Extractor
Clones the application repository.
Extracts the existing repository structure.
Provides repository context to the code generation workflow.

<br>

WF04 - Code Generation
Generates implementation files.
Normalizes file content for transport between workflows.
Validates generated files before they are sent to Git operations.

<br>

WF05 - Repository Executor
Creates a Git branch.
Writes generated files into the application repository.
Commits and pushes the branch to GitHub.

<br>

WF06 - CI/CD Executor
Triggers GitHub Actions on the generated branch.
Polls the workflow run status.
Routes the execution depending on pipeline success or failure.

<br>

WF07 - Reporting and Traceability
Builds the final execution report.
Stores the traceability matrix.
Marks the execution as completed.

<br>

WF08 - Human Review / Recovery
Handles blocked executions.
Stores errors and recovery information.
Used when a workflow cannot continue automatically.

<br>

## Troubleshooting
If n8n does not start, check that Docker Desktop is running.
If workflows cannot access external services, verify the credentials configured in n8n.
If the GitHub pipeline does not start, verify that the GitHub token has workflow permissions.
If Azure DevOps User Stories are not found, verify the tags and the Azure DevOps query used by the workflow.
If generated code fails the pipeline, check the GitHub Actions logs and the final workflow payload.

<br>

## Known Limitations
The current system processes User Stories independently.
The merge or release orchestration between multiple generated branches is not automated yet.
Manual review may be required when several branches modify the same files.
The system demonstrates an industrialized AI workflow execution chain, but it does not yet include a full automated release manager.

<br>

## Credential Dependencies for System 3
System 3 uses several external services.
Credentials are not stored in Git and must be configured manually inside the local n8n instance after importing the workflows.
After importing the workflows, each credential field must be reconnected to the correct n8n credential.

<br>

## Azure DevOps Credential

**Credential type:**
Azure DevOps Personal Access Token

**Purpose:**
Read User Stories from Azure DevOps.
Create User Stories through the bootstrap workflow.
Update User Story tags during execution.
Write execution history in Azure DevOps.

**Required permissions:**
Work Items: Read & Write
Project access to the Azure DevOps project

<br>

### Nodes using Azure DevOps credentials
| Workflow                   | Node                                     | Purpose
| ---                        | ---                                      | ---
| Bootstrap                  | 04 - Create Azure User Story             | Creates the initial User Stories automatically in Azure DevOps 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 01 - Find Decentralized User Stories     | Searches Azure DevOps for eligible User Stories 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 04 - Get Work Item Details               | Reads the selected User Story details 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 07 - Mark Work Item AI_PROCESSING        | Adds the AI_PROCESSING tag during execution 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 19 - Mark Work Item AI_COMPLETED         | Adds the AI_COMPLETED tag after successful execution 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 20 - Reset Blocked Work Item             | Updates the User Story when the execution is blocked 
| WF00 - Master Orchestrator | 21 - Force Clean Tags                    | Cleans temporary tags after execution 


<br>


## GitHub Credential

**Credential type:**
GitHub Personal Access Token or GitHub Bearer Token

**Purpose:**
Clone the application repository.
Create Git branches.
Push generated code.
Trigger GitHub Actions.
Read GitHub Actions run status.

**Required permissions:**
Repository read/write access
Workflow permission
Actions read access

<br>

### Nodes using GitHub credentials
| Workflow                           | Node                                | Purpose
| ---                                | ---                                 | ---
| WF04A - Repository Context Extr.   | 04 - Clone Repository               | Clones the application repository to extract existing project context
| WF05 - Repository Executor         | 06 - Clone Repository               | Clones the application repository before writing generated files
| WF05 - Repository Executor         | 12 - Git Push                       | Pushes the generated branch to GitHub
| WF06 - CI/CD Executor              | 04 - Trigger GitHub Actions         | Triggers the GitHub Actions pipeline on the generated branch
| WF06 - CI/CD Executor              | 07 - Get Pipeline Status            | Reads the GitHub Actions run status for the generated branch


<br>


### Local Git nodes without separate remote credentials
| Workflow                   | Node                       | Purpose
| ---                        | ---                        | ---
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 07 - Create Git Branch     | Creates the local feature branch
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 07B - Git Config User Name | Configures the local Git author name
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 07C - Git Config User Email| Configures the local Git author email
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 08 - Write Generated Files | Writes generated files into the local repository
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 09 - Git Status            | Checks local repository changes
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 10 - Git Add               | Stages generated files
| WF05 - Repository Executor | 11 - Git Commit            | Commits generated files locally

<br>

## Mistral Credential

**Credential type:**
Mistral Cloud API Key

**Purpose:**
Generate test design.
Generate implementation code.

**Required access:**
Mistral model access
Codestral model access if used

<br>

### Nodes using Mistral credentials
| Workflow                 | Node           | Purpose
| ---                      | ---            | ---
| WF03 - TDD / Test Design | Codestral 2508 | Generates pytest-oriented test design from the User Story acceptance criteria
| WF04 - Code Generation   | Codestral 2508 | Generates implementation files and test files before Git execution

<br>

## Ollama Credential

**Credential type:**
Ollama local API endpoint

**Default local endpoint:**
http://host.docker.internal:11434

**Purpose:**
Analyze requirements.
Generate technical design.
Generate reporting.
Generate recovery or governance summaries.

**Required local models:**
hermes3:8b
qwen2.5-coder:7b

<br>

### Nodes using Ollama credentials
| Workflow                         | Node                     | Purpose
| ---                              | ---                      | ---
| WF01 - Requirement Analysis      | Ollama Chat Model Hermes | Analyzes the User Story and checks if it is ready for technical design
| WF02 - Technical Design          | Ollama Chat Model Qwen   | Produces the technical design and expected project structure
| WF07 - Reporting and Traceability| Ollama Chat Model Hermes | Builds the final industrial execution report
| WF08 - Human Review / Recovery   | Ollama Chat Model Hermes | Generates recovery and governance information when the workflow is blocked

<br>

### Credential Summary
| Credential            | Required by
| ---                   | ---
| Azure DevOps PAT      | Bootstrap workflow, WF00
| GitHub token          | WF04A, WF05, WF06
| Mistral API key       | WF03, WF04
| Ollama local endpoint | WF01, WF02, WF07, WF08
